reviewText: Though Janet is not as encouraging or bubbley as the other firm instructers, this is a solid workout.  My shoulders and arms really burned during this workout.  She also works out some often skipped areas such as the inner biceps.  there is some minimal cardio work incorporated in the warm up and she keeps you stepping or marching when doing upper body work.  My heart rate is higher with this upper body workout than most.  All in all a good solid workout.  If you want another good upper body workout by the firm try the new jiggle free arms.  It is awsome.  Lots of cardio with upper body.  Also a great cross trainer with jiggle free buns (leg and bun work with a good amount of cardio also).

reviewText: The upper body moves in this workout are done in an unhurried, controlled fashion with an emphasis on good form.  By taking it slow, the muscles are isolated and muscle strength is used to lift the weight, rather than momentum.  The routine focuses on all upper body muscles - shoulders, chest, back, triceps and biceps. Modifications are shown for people who are just starting out, so it can be followed by beginners or more advanced weight trainers.For those looking to pack in as much workout as possible, lower body moves such as lunges or plié squats, can easily be incorporated into this routine.The music provides upbeat background sounds, but does not overpower Janet Brooks' training instructions. She has a very pleasant voice and instruction style.  She is encouraging without being an overly perky cheerleader type.  I have owned this DVD for a number of years and am glad it is part of my collection.

reviewText: Almost 40 minutes of upper body work! This challenging workout will leave your arms feeling like wet noodles. It is led by Janet Brooks, who does kind of remind me of "Aerobics Instructor Barbie". That isn't really a bad thing, but you may end up hating her by the end of the workout because she will work you HARD. Not a single muscle group is neglected - she hits the back, chest, arms, shoulders, and even your core.Equipment used in this video: Fanny lifter (substitute: a step), sculpting stick (substitute: broomstick), and three sets of dumbbells.This is an excellent workout to sculpt your upper body. The only problem is that it is so tough I will have to really psych myself up to do it again!
summary: Very tough workout for upper body

reviewText: This is one tough upper body workout.  37 minutes butt-kickingly difficult upper body work, but the results are worth all the delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS) and sweat.Fast & Firm Series Upper Body Sculpt is also sold as simply "Upper Body Sculpt," an add-on to the Body Sculpting System 2.  It uses the Fanny Lifter and Sculpting Stick.  She has you do uneven tricep dips and pushups off the edges of the seperated Fanny Lifter, but it is fairly easy to modify those moves if you lack the Fanny Lifter by using a chair for the tricep dips and doing your pushups on the floor.  (I've never cared for the uneven tricep dips and pushups, so this is what I always do.)  You will also need a set of 3, 5, and 8 pound dumbbells for this workout, but don't feel too badly if you have to pyramid down or skip weights altogether in parts of this video--it's quite intense and it works muscles in ways you might be unaccustomed to.  Make sure you pay attention to form in the planks segment at the end!  You can and will hurt your back if you don't do them properly, as I can attest from personal experience.  Suck those abs in and take a knee if you feel yourself compensating with your lower back.Why four out of five stars?  This is a good workout, but not a great one.  It's not as fun as some of the other workouts.  Janet isn't as encouraging and upbeat as some of the other video leads--she's more of a taskmaster.  I also think that taken on intensity level alone, it is not a good match for the other BSS2 workouts--other workouts in this set may be longer or have more cardio, but this one kicked my metaphorical butt the much, much harder than any of those workouts ever did.This is a worthwhile purchase, and you WILL see results--just don't expect a walk in the park from Janet and UBS!
summary: Upper Body Sculpt = drill sargeant in a perky blonde package

reviewText: This was my first FIRM purchase.  I don't care for the "aerobics" while you're lifting weights.  There is no warm-up.  The 1st 6 min. is with the sculpting stick.  You're lifting it quickly while moving your legs.  You can't use a heavy weight at this point.  The sets are fairly short.  Just when it starts getting intense, it's time to move on.  The instruction is clear; Janet is just a little robotic and has a scary smile throughout the workout - so do the participants. At 30 mintues you get a decent workout. You have to adjust the postion of the fanny lifter alot.  And, if you don't like push-ups beware!  There's lots of them.  You'll get a good workout.  I just didn't care for the FIRM style.

reviewText: This is a 40 minute workout that focuses primarily on the various arm, shoulder and back muscles, with nominal and brief attention to the abs.The equipment used was the Fanny Lifter, light, medium and heavy dumbbells and the Firm Sculpting Stick.  I don't have the Sculpting Stick, so I used the Firm Barbell from another era and my Transfirmer in lieu of the Fanny Lifter.  The routine does the typical quick transitioning back and forth between the use of the various pieces of equipment, perhaps even quicker than normal.I round the routine to be a tough and thorough one.  While the workout has no cardio in it, it still made me work up a little bit of a sweat.Many people have mentioned the instructor and while I won't say she's the most motivating, I thought she did a decent job.  What amuses me every time I use this workout is that she looks like she's being hypnotized, as she stares straight ahead with a wide-eyed, owl-like appearance (cue cards?).  Still, I think she does a good job of cuing and explaining the movements and is pleasant - not to mention being in great shape (especially impressive considering I read in some Firm literature that her day job is an attorney).If you want a good upper body workout, don't let the instructor detractors dissuade you from giving this one a try.
summary: Tough Upper Body Workout - Little/No Ab

reviewText: This is my first firm workout i've purchased. I am a tae bo/pilates/running girl, so i decided to give this a try after countless good reviews and infomercials about "the firm."I really enjoyed the workout, i felt my upper body sore the next day, of course in a good way.But i can't like the instructor. She is not motivating to me at all. She talks with this monotone voice. I even tried to pay attention to the Korean lady on there because i couldn't stand the instructor. She's so boring!But despite that, the workout is very effective. It is around 35 mins, the dvd is NOT chaptered, so if you don't want to do the warm up section, you must fast forward to the workout part.It seems all the firm dvd's are not divided into chapters.Also, they use the 2-1 fanny lifter (for some tricept dips, and push ups) and the bar. But I have neither and have been able to do it with no problem, I use a chair and my free weights.Despite that, i'd recommend it, it is a good workout after all, time goes actually pretty quick, and that's what matters!
summary: great workout, but instructor really boring

reviewText: I recently bought this video and it's very tough. If you can get past the fact that the instructor is annoying, it's a good workout.You do a lot of pushups in this video, but they're not the typical kind. One variation using The Firm Fanny Lifter (completely stacked), is where you lie across it, and depending on your skill level, you solely leave your thighs on it, or just your lower legs/feet, as you support your upper body with your hands on the floor. That exercise is  a little uncomfortable since the fanny lifter digs into your skin. There are other pushup variations where the fanny lifter is just a place to rest your hands.There is also a variation of triceps dips, which is tough. You set the blue and the purple sections of the fanny lifter  next to one another and sit on the floor with your back to them, resting a hand on each section. Then, depending on your skill level, you do the movement with your legs straight out in front of you, or legs bent and out in front. That exercise is a little bit awkward and has taken some getting used to.Aside from those exercises, you do work for your biceps, shoulders, back, and chest. There are also other triceps exercises using weights and the sculpting stick.This video will take some getting used to, especially if you're new to exercising. And if you can focus on the work you're doing, rather than how annoying Janet is, it'll be over before you know it.
